This article is a transcript of remarks made by Governor Jerry Brown and President Donald Trump during their visit to Chico, California in response to the devastating wildfires in the state. Both leaders expressed gratitude for the efforts of firefighters and first responders and praised the collaboration between different agencies and levels of government. The President acknowledged the severity of the situation and the unprecedented level of destruction caused by the fires. FEMA Administrator Brock Long outlined the assistance being provided by FEMA, including disaster recovery centers and financial aid for affected individuals. The President and Governor discussed the need for better forest management and the allocation of funds for this purpose. They also touched on the issue of climate change, with the President reiterating his stance on the importance of both a healthy climate and safe forests. Overall, the remarks highlighted the ongoing efforts to fight the fires, provide assistance to affected communities, and address the underlying causes of the wildfires.